Yes, absolutely. From a production and security perspective, you should never assume Ping/Keycloak/OIDC will always return all three tokens.

Right now you have something like:

```java
String accessToken = (String) tokenResponse.get("access_token");
String idToken = (String) tokenResponse.get("id_token");
String refreshToken = (String) tokenResponse.get("refresh_token");
```

Then immediately:

```java
JwtUserClaims claims = jwtService.extractClaims(idToken);
```

If `id_token` is missing, you'll get a NullPointerException or JWT parsing exception later, which makes debugging harder.

---

## Recommended approach

Add a helper:

```java
private String getRequiredToken(
        Map<String, Object> tokenResponse,
        String tokenName) {

    Object value = tokenResponse.get(tokenName);

    if (!(value instanceof String token) || token.isBlank()) {
        throw new TechnicalException(
                "Missing token in response: " + tokenName);
    }

    return token;
}
```

Then:

```java
String accessToken = getRequiredToken(tokenResponse, "access_token");
String idToken = getRequiredToken(tokenResponse, "id_token");
String refreshToken = getRequiredToken(tokenResponse, "refresh_token");
```

---

## Even better

Validate the whole token response once:

```java
private void validateTokenResponse(Map<String, Object> tokenResponse) {

    if (tokenResponse == null) {
        throw new TechnicalException("Token response is null");
    }

    validateRequiredField(tokenResponse, "access_token");
    validateRequiredField(tokenResponse, "id_token");
    validateRequiredField(tokenResponse, "refresh_token");
}

private void validateRequiredField(
        Map<String, Object> tokenResponse,
        String fieldName) {

    Object value = tokenResponse.get(fieldName);

    if (!(value instanceof String token) || token.isBlank()) {
        throw new TechnicalException(
                "Missing required token field: " + fieldName);
    }
}
```

Usage:

```java
Map<String, Object> tokenResponse =
        exchangeToken(code, tokenUrl, appConfig, tx);

validateTokenResponse(tokenResponse);
```

Then safely read the values.

